  "query": "How does rotational burning compare to leaving unburned patches during prescribed fires for butterfly populations in US prairies?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from 17 studies on rotational burning and 2 studies on leaving unburned patches shows different effects on butterfly populations in US prairies. Rotational burning (burning different areas on a 1-6 year cycle) increased butterfly species richness in pine-oak barrens and semi-natural grasslands compared to unmanaged sites, though effects were mixed compared to sites managed by annual burning or mowing. Rotational burning resulted in higher total abundance on prairies burned more than one, two or four years ago versus recently burned areas. In contrast, leaving areas unburned during prescribed burning increased abundance of Karner blue butterflies over 2-3 years in oak savannas and prairies. Specialist butterfly species showed varying responses to unburned patches: six out of nine were more abundant, one was less abundant, and two had similar abundance compared to sites without unburned areas. Karner blue butterflies were recorded using all 11 unburned patches surveyed within managed areas.",
