{
  "query": "What does the evidence say about the long-term success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation or captive-release?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence shows mixed long-term success for butterfly population re-establishment through translocation or captive-release programs. For translocation (3909), 16 studies found that translocated butterfly populations persisted for 2-49 years with some increasing in abundance, while one review reported only 25% of translocated populations survived for at least three years and only 8% survived for more than 10 years. Another review found that translocated large copper populations survived for up to 38 years but ultimately died out or required supplementation. For captive-release programs (3914), 13 studies reported that captive-bred butterfly populations persisted for 2-28 years and increased in abundance, while other populations died out within 1-2 years or required continued releases to survive. One review found identical survival statistics: 25% of captive-bred populations survived for at least three years and only 8% survived for more than 10 years.",
